Scortum is inserted by Bentley after inuocabant. 1 h'ave not incorporated it into the text, but I believe it to be correct, for the fol- lowing reasons: (1) it is certain that a word has dropped out ; (2) scortum has to be mentally supplied, in any case, to make sense, even if omitted from the text ; (3) the preceding lines show that the speaker is making the most of this word by constant repetition and by centering the thought upon it; (4) the word would easily be omitted by a scribe, who, glancing up from his copy for a moment, after reading inuocatmn would, upon turning again to his copy, mistake the —tum of scortum for the last syllable copied, and would begin writing again with an non, etc. The loss of <esst est), supplied fflamerarim, could not be so easily accounted for.
